In [15]:
for col_name in df.drop(columns = 'Class').columns:     # Dropping the outliers 
    q1 = df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
    high = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
    
    df.loc[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high), col_name] = df[col_name].median()

In [18]:
from pandas.plotting import andrews_curves
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
andrews_curves(df, "Class", color=['crimson','silver','steelblue'],samples=200)
plt.title('Andrews Curves Plot', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
plt.legend(loc=1, prop={'size': 10}, frameon=True,shadow=True, facecolor="white", edgecolor="black")
plt.show()

Andrews curves allows to plot multivariate data as a large number of curves that are created using the attributes of samples as coefficients for Fourier series. By coloring these curves differently for each class it is possible to visualize data clustering. Curves belonging to samples of the same class will usually be closer together and form larger structures.

df.corr() computes pairwise correlation of columns.

  • Correlation shows how two variables are related to each other.
  • Positive values shows as one variable increases other variable increases as well.
  • Negative values shows as one variable increases other variable decreases.
  • Bigger values show high correlation between variables while smaller values show less correlation.

4. Data Pre-processing:¶

In [23]:
X = df.drop(['Class'], axis=1, inplace=False)  #Features
y = df['Class']                                #Target

The dataset contains 7 columns : P_incidence, P_tilt, L_angle, S_slope,P_radius,S_Degree and Class.

The actual features are described by columns 0-6. Last column contains lables of samples. The data is now split into two arrays: X(features) and y(labels)

In [81]:
neig = np.arange(1,25)            # Finding the best k value
train_accuracy = []
test_accuracy = []
for i, k in enumerate(neig):      # Loop over different values of k
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k,weights='distance')
    knn.fit(X_train_res,y_train_res)
    prediction = knn.predict(X_test)
    train_accuracy.append(knn.score(X_train_res, y_train_res))
    test_accuracy.append(knn.score(X_test, y_test)) 
print("Best accuracy is {} with K = {}".format(np.max(test_accuracy)*100,1+test_accuracy.index(np.max(test_accuracy))))

Best accuracy is 88.70967741935483 with K = 5

6. Conclusion:¶

  • The Accuracy of the KNN model with K=3 is 85.48%.
  • The Accuracy of the KNN model with K=5 is found to be the best fit model with score of 88.70% which is almost 4 percent more than regular KNN model.
  • Type_H has a recall of 92%, which means that among the patients with Type_H condition The KNN model predicted 92% of them to have Type_H condition.
  • Type_S has recall of 80%, which means that among the patients with Type_S condition The KNN model predicted 80% of them to have Type_S condition.
  • type_S has a precision of 96%, The model predicted the correct type 96% times. we can infer that the model has done really well in prediction Type_S condition as it has high recall and precision.

  • For Noraml condition the model predicted 78% of the data correctly.

Suggestions for Future Data collection:¶

  • Clearer description and understanding of what the features means should be provided for better analysis and feature engineering.
  • More data should be recorded from patients as the sample-set was too low (310) to build a usable model for prediction.
  • Much better results can be obtained if the target had only two classes Normal and Abnormal on the given 310 datapoints.
  • Various methods should be implemented to record more data and addition of new features from X-rays, CT-scans and MRI's.
